1	# Level authoring
2	
3	`raild` treats each level as an independent module under `src/levels/<level-id>/`. For comparison tasks, a level uses the shared `createLockOnRunner` flow while owning its rail, spawns, enemy motion, visuals, environment, effects, and procedural audio.
4	
5	Shared code lives in `src/engine/`:
6	
7	- `lock-on-runner.ts` contains the START/RUN/REPLAY flow, pointer input, lock-on targeting, homing shots, scoring hooks, and HUD updates;
8	- `rail.ts` contains rail sampling helpers, not a level rail;
9	- `rail-pacer.ts` contains an opt-in helper for high-speed levels that need enemies to pace the camera for an authored readable window;
10	- `music.ts` contains small timing helpers for beat emission, tempo, MIDI conversion, and grid quantization;
11	- `music-time.ts` converts authored bars, beats, steps, and named markers into the seconds consumed by gameplay systems;
12	- `audio-kit.ts` contains Web Audio primitives plus the shared mix bus and instrument registry;
13	- `audio-voices.ts` contains the declarative voice-spec layer that compiles compact timbre specs to the audio-kit primitives;
14	- `audio-trace.ts` contains semantic audio trace sinks and the reusable trace harness;
15	- `score.ts` contains the shared musical-position helper for epoch anchoring, harmony, sections, action quantization, and kill lanes;
16	- `arrangement.ts` contains the thin section/pattern/function/one-shot DSL for musical scheduling;
17	- `spawn-patterns.ts` contains small helpers for eager spawn timeline construction;
18	- `speed-profile.ts` contains piecewise-linear speed factors and normalized-integral run-progress easing for authored speed curves;
19	- `glyphs.ts` contains neutral 5×7 glyph grid data and accessors, not rendering;
20	- `hostile-shot.ts` contains shared homing steer, behind-camera despawn cull, and approach/impact timing for lockable enemy shots and hazards;
21	- `visual-kit.ts` contains lifecycle helpers for visual bookkeeping: pending mesh-to-eve

